All "sorts" of sort(ing algorithms)

Insertion Sort

Insertion sort is awful in terms of performance, but great in terms of implementation. Essentially, you just have an outer loop that looks at the next element in your array and the inner loop swaps it to the left until it's greater than or equal to the element to it's left (or it is swapped all the way to index 0). The outer loop always runs N times and in the worse case, the inner loop has to keep swapping until it moves the element all the way to index 0 (which is O(N)) so insertions sort is O(pow(N, 2)).

Merge Sort

Merge sort works by first, sorting the left and right halves of it's input (recursively) if the input has more than 1 element in it, then merging those two sorted vectors/lists. Merging two sorted vectors/lists is relatively simple: you just keep looking at the next element in each vector/list, then you take the smaller one of the two and output it. Since each element is processed once in O(1) time, the total time is O(N) for N elements.

We know then that if T(N) is the amount of time it takes to sort a vector, then T(0) = T(1) ≈ 1 and T(N) ≈ T(N / 2) + T(N / 2) + N. If we can solve this equation, we can solve for the big-O of merge sort.

T(0) = T(1)≈1definition
T(N)≈T(N / 2) + T(N / 2) + Ndefinition
T(N)≈2 * T(N / 2) + Nsimplify
T(N)≈2 * (2 * T(N / 4) + N / 2) + Nrecurse: replace T(N / 2) with definition
T(N)≈4 * T(N / 4) + 2 * Nsimplify
T(N)≈4 * (2 * T(N / 8) + N / 4) + 2 * Nrecurse: replace T(N / 4) with definition
T(N)≈8 * T(N / 8) + 3 * Nsimplify
T(N)≈16 * (2 * T(N / 16) + N / 8) + 3 * Nrecurse: replace T(N / 8) with definition
T(N)≈16 * T(N / 16) + 4 * Nsimplify
T(N)≈pow(2, R) * T(N / pow(2, R)) + R * Nnotice pattern

At this point, we know what happens every time we 'recurse', but we still don't know what T(N / pow(2, R)) is. However, we do know that T(1) = 1, so if we can solve for N / pow(2, R) = 1, we can just replace T(N / pow(2, R)) with 1!

N / pow(2, R)=1
N=pow(2, R)multiply by pow(2, R)
log(N) / log(2)=Rtake log base 2

Now we can continue where we left off earlier:

T(N)≈pow(2, R) * T(N / pow(2, R)) + R * N
T(N)≈pow(2, log(N) / log(2)) * T(N / pow(2, log(N) / log(2))) + log(N) / log(2) * Nlet R = log(N) / log(2)
T(N)≈N * T(N / N) + log(N) / log(2) * Nsimplify
T(N)≈N * T(1) + log(N) / log(2) * Nsimplify
T(N)≈N + log(N) / log(2) * Nsimplify
T(N)∈N * log(N)big-O

Heap Sort

Heap sort takes an vector (or something similar) as input, turns it into a max heap in place, then repeatedly pops the largest element from the heap and places it at the next, just past the max heap.

Quick Sort

Quick sort works by randomly selecting an element, called the pivot, in the input vector, then partitioning everything that's less than and greater than that pivot to the left and right halves of the input, then it recursively calls itself on the left and right halves. On average, this ends up splitting the input in about half and has an average running time of O(N * log(N)), just like Merge sort. However, if we were to get very unlucky, we could always end up picking a bad pivot such that one partition has 1 or 2 elements and the other N - 1 or N - 2 elements end up in the other parition, so each time we recurse we might end up doing N + (N - 1) + (N - 2) + ... + 3 + 2 + 1 work which is O(pow(N, 2)). In practice, you have to get very unlucky for this to happen though.

Benchmarking

Benchmarking is testing the relative or absolute performance of something, such as how long an algorithm takes to run. Its easy to make mistakes when measuring how fast something is. For example, if you want to benchmark a sorting algorithm, you might start by generating a random vector of ints, then seeing how long it takes to sort it. If you tried sorting strings instead, you will probably get very different results. If you tried running it on a different computer, you will probably get different results. If the computer you're running it on is also busy performing other calculations, you will probably get different results. Even if you run the same code repeatedly, chances are that you'll get different results. This is because there's a lot more going on than just the sorting algorithm. Computers multitask (see Operating system process scheduler) and sometimes you'll get slightly more time than other times. Different CPUs make different tradeoffs, so they perform some operations faster/slower than other CPUs. This doesn't mean that benchmarking and timing is a bad idea, but that you need to be careful about how you interpret the results.

An code example:

#include <algorithm>
#include <chrono>
#include <cmath>
#include <cstdio>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cstring>
#include <iostream>

using namespace std::chrono;

// A class for timing how long soething takes.
class SimpleTimer {
  high_resolution_clock::time_point start_time;
public:
  void start() {
    start_time = high_resolution_clock::now();
  }
  double seconds_elapsed() {
    return duration_cast<duration<double>>(
        high_resolution_clock::now() - start_time).count();
  }
};


void bubble_sort(std::vector<long>& nums) {
  bool did_swap = false;
  do {
    did_swap = false;
    for (int j = 1; j < nums.size(); ++j) {
      if (nums[j] < nums[j - 1]) {
        std::swap(nums[j], nums[j - 1]);
        did_swap = true;
      }
    }
  } while (did_swap);
}

// parition all values in the nums between low (inclusive) and high (exclusive)
// so that all values < partition_value are in the lower/left part of
// nums and all values >= partition_value are in the upper/right part of nums.
// return the index of the first value that is >= partition_value
// (where the partitions are separated)
int partition(std::vector<long>& nums, long partition_value, int low, int high) {
  int low_next = low, high_next = high - 1;
  // This loop goes through the nums and moves anything that's < partition_value
  // to the left/lower part of the nums and everyting that's >= partition_value
  // to the right/upper part of the nums.
  while (low_next < high_next) {
    if (nums[low_next] < partition_value) {
      ++low_next;
    } else if (nums[high_next] >= partition_value) {
      --high_next;
    } else {
      std::swap(nums[low_next], nums[high_next]);
    }
  }
  return low_next;
}

// Do a quick sort in-place
void quick_sort_helper(std::vector<long>& nums, int low, int high) {
  if (high - low <= 1 || std::is_sorted(nums.begin() + low, nums.begin() + high)) {
    return;
  }
  long partition_value = nums[rand() % (high - low) + low];
  // Now, we recurse on each partition (all the < stuff and all the >= stuff).
  int partition_index = partition(nums, partition_value, low, high);
  quick_sort_helper(nums, low, partition_index);
  quick_sort_helper(nums, partition_index, high);
}

void quick_sort(std::vector<long>& nums) {
  quick_sort_helper(nums, 0, nums.size());
}

// Given two start/end iterator pairs that can be used to iterate over two
// sorted things and an output iterator, merge the two sorted inputs into
// the output.
template <typename Iter, typename OutputIter>
void merge_sorted(Iter a, Iter a_end, Iter b, Iter b_end, OutputIter output) {
  while (a != a_end && b != b_end) {
    if (*a < *b) {
      *output = *a;
      ++a;
    } else {
      *output = *b;
      ++b;
    }
    ++output;
  }
  while (a != a_end) {
    *output = *a;
    ++a;
    ++output;
  }
  while (b != b_end) {
    *output = *b;
    ++b;
    ++output;
  }
}

void merge_sort_helper(std::vector<long>& nums, std::vector<long>& scratch,
                       int low, int high) {
  if (high - low <= 1 || std::is_sorted(nums.begin() + low, nums.begin() + high)) {
    return;
  }
  int mid = (low + high) / 2;
  merge_sort_helper(nums, scratch, low, mid);
  merge_sort_helper(nums, scratch, mid, high);
  // merge the sorted halves (into the scratch buffer)
  std::vector<long>::iterator b = nums.begin();
  merge_sorted(b + low, b + mid, b + mid, b + high, scratch.begin() + low);
  // copy from the scratch buffer back to nums
  std::copy(scratch.begin() + low, scratch.begin() + high, i + low);
}

void merge_sort(std::vector<long>& nums) {
  std::vector<long> scratch(nums.size());
  merge_sort_helper(nums, scratch, 0, nums.size());
}

void std_sort(std::vector<long>& nums) {
  std::sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
}

void null_sort(std::vector<long>& nums) {
  // This doesn't actually sort anything. It's used so we can see
  // how accurate the timing code is.
}

double time_to_sort(
    void (*sort)(std::vector<long>&),
    int size, int num_iterations) {
  SimpleTimer timer;
  std::vector<long> nums(size, 0);  // vector of 1000 0's
  double total_seconds = 0.0;
  for (int i = 0; i < num_iterations; ++i) {
    for (int j = 0; j < nums.size(); ++j) {
      nums[j] = rand();
    }
    // std_sort(nums);
    timer.start();
    sort(nums);
    total_seconds += timer.seconds_elapsed();
    if (!std::is_sorted(nums.begin(), nums.end()) && sort != null_sort) {
      std::cerr << "Numbers are not really sorted!" << std::endl;
    }
  }
  return total_seconds;
}

// To use this program, compile it, then pipe it to "gnuplot -p"
// Note that bubble_sort is not used below because it grows so fast, that it's
// difficult to see how the other sorting algorithms behave differently.
int main() {
  printf("set key left top;"
         "plot "
         "'-' using 1:2 title 'quick sort' with points, "
         "'-' using 1:2 title 'merge sort' with points, "
         "'-' using 1:2 title 'std::sort' with points, "
         "'-' using 1:2 title 'nothing' with points;\n");
  for (void (*sort)(std::vector<long>&) : {
      quick_sort, merge_sort, std_sort, null_sort}) {
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {
      int size = 10 * i;
      int num_iterations = 10;
      double sort_seconds = time_to_sort(sort, size, num_iterations);
      printf("%d %f\n", size, sort_seconds);
    }
    printf("e\n");
  }
  return 0;
}
$ clang -Wall -lstdc++ -std=c++11 timing_sorting_algorithms.cpp && ./a.out | gnuplot -persist

Indirect Sorting

Imagine that you had to sort a list of large objects, each one taking up 1/1,000 of your computer's total memory. Even though, it's a small list, each item is huge and slow to swap. Ideally, we'd use an algorithm that made as few swaps or moves as possible. Indirect Sorting accomplishes this by first creating a list of pointers to the data you want to sort, then comparing what the pointers point to and swapping the pointers instead. After the pointers are "sorted", you only have to swap O(N) elements (one swap or move per element), instead of O(N * log(N)) times.
